1–3. Difference between git merge and git rebase
Git Merge: Combines changes from one branch into another, creating a new commit that preserves history.

Git Rebase: Moves or reapplies commits from one branch onto another, rewriting history for a cleaner linear timeline.

Use cases:

Merge → when you want to preserve history and context of feature development.

Rebase → when you want a clean, linear history without merge commits.

Pros & Cons:

Feature	Merge	Rebase
History	Preserves	Rewrites
Clarity	Shows branch structure	Linear, cleaner
Safety	Safer (no rewrite)	Risky if misused
Collaboration	Good for shared branches	Best for local cleanup


4–5. Git Stash
Temporarily saves uncommitted changes so you can switch branches or pull updates without losing work.

Use case: You’re in the middle of coding but need to quickly switch branches.

bash


Copy
git stash       # save changes
git stash pop   # reapply changes
6 & 22. Git Cherry-pick
Applies a specific commit from one branch onto another.

Use case: You want a bug fix from another branch without merging all its changes.

7–9 & 25. Branching Strategy
Common strategies:

Git Flow: main, develop, feature branches, release branches.

GitHub Flow: main + short-lived feature branches, PR-based.

Trunk-based: Developers commit directly to main with feature flags.

Pros/Cons:

Git Flow → structured, good for big teams, but complex.

GitHub Flow → simple, fast, but less control.

Trunk-based → very agile, but risky without discipline.

10–11, 25–26. Merge Conflicts
Occur when Git cannot automatically reconcile differences between branches.

Resolution:

Open conflicted file.

Choose correct changes (yours, theirs, or manual merge).

Mark resolved and commit.

12–13 & 20. Git Pull vs Git Fetch
Fetch: Downloads changes but doesn’t merge.

Pull: Fetch + merge (or rebase).

Use case: Use fetch when you want to review before merging.

14–15. Git vs GitHub vs Bitbucket
Git: Version control system.

GitHub: Cloud hosting + collaboration platform.

Bitbucket: Similar to GitHub, integrates tightly with Jira/Atlassian.

16. SCM (Source Control Management)
Tools/processes to manage code versions, history, collaboration.

17. Purpose of Branches
Isolate features, bug fixes, experiments without affecting main codebase.

18. Git Push
Sends local commits to remote repository.

19. Clone GitHub Repo
